\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2}{\ignorespaces \textbf  {KCOR workflow: four-step \(\mittheta _{0,d}\) estimation, then normalization and comparison.} \textbf  {(A)} Fixed-cohort cumulative hazards are stabilized after enrollment, and event time is rebased so that frailty identification targets enrollment-time \(\mittheta _{0,d}\). \textbf  {(B)} Steps 1-4 estimate \(\mittheta _{0,d}\): a seed Gompertz fit is obtained in the nearest quiet window, the effective cumulative hazard is reconstructed over the full trajectory using all weeks, persistent offsets are aligned across quiet windows, and \(\mittheta _{0,d}\) is refit across the pooled quiet windows with \(\hat {k}_d\) held fixed. Reconstruction, offset alignment, and pooled refitting iterate to convergence before gamma-frailty inversion and KCOR computation. \textbf  {(C)} In epidemic-wave applications, an optional NPH exponent module may define the preprocessing hazard stream before accumulation and inversion; this module is not part of the universal KCOR core and is interpreted only when its cross-cohort identification diagnostics are credible. \emph  {This schematic is illustrative rather than empirical. In the schematic, \(\tilde H_{0,d}(t)\) denotes the depletion-neutralized baseline cumulative hazard and \(\mittheta _{0,d}\) denotes enrollment-time frailty variance after the stabilization skip.}}}{16}{figure.2}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:kcor_workflow}{{2}{16}{\textbf {KCOR workflow: four-step \(\theta _{0,d}\) estimation, then normalization and comparison.} \textbf {(A)} Fixed-cohort cumulative hazards are stabilized after enrollment, and event time is rebased so that frailty identification targets enrollment-time \(\theta _{0,d}\). \textbf {(B)} Steps 1-4 estimate \(\theta _{0,d}\): a seed Gompertz fit is obtained in the nearest quiet window, the effective cumulative hazard is reconstructed over the full trajectory using all weeks, persistent offsets are aligned across quiet windows, and \(\theta _{0,d}\) is refit across the pooled quiet windows with \(\hat {k}_d\) held fixed. Reconstruction, offset alignment, and pooled refitting iterate to convergence before gamma-frailty inversion and KCOR computation. \textbf {(C)} In epidemic-wave applications, an optional NPH exponent module may define the preprocessing hazard stream before accumulation and inversion; this module is not part of the universal KCOR core and is interpreted only when its cross-cohort identification diagnostics are credible. \emph {This schematic is illustrative rather than empirical. In the schematic, \(\tilde H_{0,d}(t)\) denotes the depletion-neutralized baseline cumulative hazard and \(\theta _{0,d}\) denotes enrollment-time frailty variance after the stabilization skip.}}{figure.2}{}}
